import ErgodicTheory.Krieger.ZIterate
import Mathlib.MeasureTheory.MeasurableSpace.EventuallyMeasurable
import Mathlib.MeasureTheory.Measure.QuasiMeasurePreserving

/-!
# The coding layer for Krieger's finite generator theorem: two-sided recovery (Krieger M3)

This file is the **œÉ-algebra recovery core** of Krieger's finite generator theorem. The classical
proof (Krieger 1970; Einsiedler‚ÄìLindenstrauss‚ÄìWard *Entropy in Ergodic Theory* ¬ß3) builds a finite
`Fin k`-valued partition `P` by *coding* the columns of a Rokhlin tower so that the two-sided
`P`-itinerary of a.e. point recovers its full itinerary under a fixed countable generator `Q`. The
combinatorial heart ‚Äî that `log k > h` forces the number of `N`-names to be `‚â§ k·¥∫` up to `Œµ`, so a
`Fin k` code exists ‚Äî is supplied upstream (the name-count layer M2, the Rokhlin tower M1). What
remains, and is proved here unconditionally, is the **recovery half**: *once* a candidate code `P`
has the property that every cell of `Q` is recovered, **mod 0**, by the two-sided `P`-saturation,
`P` two-sidedly generates **mod 0** whenever `Q` does.

## Why *mod 0*: generators in ergodic theory generate up to null sets

The classical Krieger construction produces a code map that is defined and invertible only
**Œº-almost everywhere**, so it recovers each generator cell only **modulo a Œº-null set**. This is
not an artefact of the formalization: in ergodic theory a "generator" *always* means **mod 0** ‚Äî a
partition generates the œÉ-algebra *up to null sets* ‚Äî because the ambient œÉ-algebra `mŒ±` of a
standard-Borel space is **not** `Œº`-complete, so an a.e.-defined code can never establish a
*literal* œÉ-algebra equality with `mŒ±`. (See Glasner, *Ergodic Theory via Joinings*; Einsiedler‚Äì
Lindenstrauss‚ÄìWard, *Entropy in Ergodic Theory*, Ch. 2 on generators; Downarowicz ¬ß4.2, where the
strong-generator condition is `ùìë = œÉ(‚ãÉ‚Çô T‚Åø Œ±)` **mod Œº**.) The literal equality
`twoSidedSat e P = mŒ±` is therefore *too strong / non-standard*, and the unconditional Krieger
construction provably cannot discharge it; the mod-0 condition is the faithful one.

We formalize "mod 0" with Mathlib's **`MeasureTheory.eventuallyMeasurableSpace m‚ÇÄ (ae Œº)`**: the
œÉ-algebra of sets that are `=·µê[Œº]`-equal to an `m‚ÇÄ`-measurable set (the `Œº`-completion of the
sub-œÉ-algebra `m‚ÇÄ`). Crucially this keeps every statement at the level of an order relation `‚â§`
between `MeasurableSpace Œ±` *values*, with the ambient measure `Œº` fixed against `mŒ±` ‚Äî so the
proofs never rewrite the œÉ-algebra index of `Œº` (which would break, since `Measure Œ±` is indexed by
its `MeasurableSpace`).

## The two-sided saturation and its (literal and mod-0) shift-invariance

For `e : Œ± ‚âÉ·µê Œ±` and a finite partition `P`, write
`twoSidedSat e P := ‚®Ü n : ‚Ñ§, comap (e‚Åø) œÉ(P)`
for the œÉ-algebra generated by the whole two-sided `P`-itinerary. The single structural fact that
drives everything is **shift-invariance**: pulling `twoSidedSat e P` back by any iterate `e·µê` lands
inside `twoSidedSat e P` again, because reindexing the `‚Ñ§`-supremum `n ‚Ü¶ n + m` is a bijection of
`‚Ñ§` (`comap_twoSidedSat_le`). This is precisely where two-sidedness (`‚®Ü` over `‚Ñ§`, not `‚Ñï`) is
load-bearing: a forward `‚Ñï`-supremum is *not* shift-invariant under the backward iterate `e‚Åª¬π`.

The mod-0 layer lifts this: for a **measure-preserving** `e`, preimage under `e·µê` commutes with the
`Œº`-completion (`comap_eventuallyMeasurableSpace_le`, using that a measure-preserving map is
quasi-measure-preserving so `s =·µê t ‚üπ f‚Åª¬πs =·µê f‚Åª¬πt`), and the completion is monotone and idempotent
(`eventuallyMeasurableSpace_mono`, `eventuallyMeasurableSpace_idem`). These give mod-0
shift-invariance (`comap_eventuallyMeasurableSpace_twoSidedSat_le`) and the mod-0 recovery
monotonicity (`twoSidedSat_mono_of_codes`), so a mod-0 generator `Q` lifts to a mod-0 generator `P`
(`IsGeneratingTwoSidedMod0.of_codes`).

## The recovery machinery consumed by the coding layer

The headline's coding step is phrased through the **cross-layer** predicate
`ErgodicTheory.Krieger.CodesTwoSidedMod0c` (`Generator.lean`), which packages the **mod-0** recovery
hypothesis `œÉ(Q) ‚â§ eventuallyMeasurableSpace (twoSidedSat e P) (ae Œº)` ‚Äî every cell of `Q` is
recovered mod 0 by the two-sided `P`-saturation ‚Äî and turns the *existence* of a `Fin k`-valued
`P` with that property into `IsGeneratingTwoSidedMod0 e P`. This file supplies the `Fintype`-layer
machinery that predicate is built on: the two-sided saturation `twoSidedSat`, its (literal and
mod-0) shift-invariance, the Œº-completion functoriality, and the recovery-monotonicity lemmas
(`twoSidedSat_mono_of_codes`, `IsGeneratingTwoSidedMod0.of_codes`) promoting a mod-0 generator `Q`
to a mod-0 generator `P` once every cell of `Q` is recovered mod 0 by the two-sided `P`-itinerary.

## Main definitions

* `ErgodicTheory.Krieger.twoSidedSat`: the two-sided itinerary œÉ-algebra `‚®Ü n : ‚Ñ§, comap (e‚Åø) œÉ(P)`.
* `ErgodicTheory.Krieger.IsGeneratingTwoSidedMod0`: `P` two-sidedly generates **mod 0**.

## Main results

* `ErgodicTheory.Krieger.comap_twoSidedSat_le`: (literal) shift-invariance of the two-sided
  saturation.
* `ErgodicTheory.Krieger.comap_eventuallyMeasurableSpace_twoSidedSat_le`: mod-0 shift-invariance.
* `ErgodicTheory.Krieger.twoSidedSat_mono_of_codes`: mod-0 recovery monotonicity.
* `ErgodicTheory.Krieger.IsGeneratingTwoSidedMod0.of_codes`: recovery lifts a mod-0 two-sided
  generator.
* `ErgodicTheory.Krieger.isGeneratingTwoSidedMod0_of_literal`: faithfulness ‚Äî the (non-standard)
  literal condition is *stronger* than the (standard) mod-0 one.

## References

* Wolfgang Krieger, *On entropy and generators of measure-preserving transformations*,
  Trans. Amer. Math. Soc. **149** (1970), 453‚Äì464.
* Manfred Einsiedler, Elon Lindenstrauss and Thomas Ward, *Entropy in Ergodic Theory and
  Homogeneous Dynamics* (book in progress), Ch. 2 (generators, mod 0) and ¬ß3 (the Krieger generator
  theorem).
* Eli Glasner, *Ergodic Theory via Joinings*, Math. Surveys Monogr. **101**, AMS (2003) ‚Äî Krieger
  chapter (generators are mod 0).
* Tomasz Downarowicz, *Entropy in Dynamical Systems*, Cambridge (2011), ¬ß4.2 (the strong-generator
  condition holds mod Œº).
-/

open MeasureTheory Function MeasurableSpace Filter

namespace ErgodicTheory.Krieger

variable {Œ± : Type*} {Œπ Œ∫ : Type*} [mŒ± : MeasurableSpace Œ±] [Fintype Œπ] [Fintype Œ∫]
  {Œº : Measure Œ±}

open ErgodicTheory.Entropy

/-- The **two-sided itinerary œÉ-algebra** of a finite partition `P` under the automorphism `e`:
the supremum, over all integer iterates `e‚Åø` (`n : ‚Ñ§`), of the pulled-back generating œÉ-algebra
`œÉ(P)`. A set is `twoSidedSat e P`-measurable exactly when it is determined by the (two-sided)
`P`-itinerary `n ‚Ü¶ (the cell of P containing e‚Åø x)`. By the design note above, the correct
two-sided generation condition asks for `twoSidedSat e P` to be the ambient œÉ-algebra **mod 0**
(`IsGeneratingTwoSidedMod0`), not literally. Marked `@[reducible]` (its value is a
`MeasurableSpace`, a class type) so it unfolds for instance resolution and definitional rewriting,
mirroring `ErgodicTheory.Entropy.generatedSigmaAlgebra`. -/
@[reducible]
noncomputable def twoSidedSat (e : Œ± ‚âÉ·µê Œ±) (P : MeasurePartition Œº Œπ) : MeasurableSpace Œ± :=
  ‚®Ü n : ‚Ñ§, MeasurableSpace.comap (ziter e n) (generatedSigmaAlgebra Œº P)

@[simp]
lemma twoSidedSat_def (e : Œ± ‚âÉ·µê Œ±) (P : MeasurePartition Œº Œπ) :
    twoSidedSat e P = ‚®Ü n : ‚Ñ§, MeasurableSpace.comap (ziter e n) (generatedSigmaAlgebra Œº P) :=
  rfl

/-- **Shift-invariance of the two-sided saturation.** Pulling the two-sided itinerary œÉ-algebra
`twoSidedSat e P` back by any iterate `e·µê` lands inside it again:
`comap (e·µê) (twoSidedSat e P) ‚â§ twoSidedSat e P`.

A generator of `comap (e·µê) (twoSidedSat e P)` is `e·µê‚Åª¬π` of a generator of one of the `‚Ñ§`-terms,
namely `comap (e·µê) (comap (e‚Åø) œÉ(P)) = comap (e‚Åø ‚àò e·µê) œÉ(P) = comap (e^{n+m}) œÉ(P)` (using
`ziter_add`), which is the `(n + m)`-th term of the same `‚Ñ§`-supremum. This is *exactly* where the
two-sided (`‚Ñ§`) indexing is essential: the reindexing `n ‚Ü¶ n + m` is a bijection of `‚Ñ§`, so no
terms are lost ‚Äî a forward (`‚Ñï`) supremum would lose terms under a backward shift. -/
theorem comap_twoSidedSat_le (e : Œ± ‚âÉ·µê Œ±) (P : MeasurePartition Œº Œπ) (m : ‚Ñ§) :
    MeasurableSpace.comap (ziter e m) (twoSidedSat e P) ‚â§ twoSidedSat e P := by
  rw [twoSidedSat_def, MeasurableSpace.comap_iSup]
  refine iSup_le fun n => ?_
  rw [MeasurableSpace.comap_comp, ‚Üê ziter_add]
  exact le_iSup (fun k : ‚Ñ§ => MeasurableSpace.comap (ziter e k) (generatedSigmaAlgebra Œº P)) (n + m)

/-! ### The Œº-completion of a sub-œÉ-algebra, and its functoriality

We use `MeasureTheory.eventuallyMeasurableSpace m‚ÇÄ (ae Œº)` ‚Äî the œÉ-algebra of sets `=·µê[Œº]`-equal to
an `m‚ÇÄ`-measurable set ‚Äî as the **Œº-completion** of the sub-œÉ-algebra `m‚ÇÄ`. The three lemmas below
(monotonicity, idempotence, and `comap`-commutation for a measure-preserving map) are all that the
mod-0 recovery needs; each keeps everything at the level of `MeasurableSpace`-`‚â§`. -/

/-- **Monotonicity of the Œº-completion.** If `m‚ÇÄ ‚â§ m‚ÇÅ` then their Œº-completions are ordered the same
way: an `m‚ÇÄ`-measurable approximant of `s` is in particular an `m‚ÇÅ`-measurable approximant. -/
theorem eventuallyMeasurableSpace_mono {m‚ÇÄ m‚ÇÅ : MeasurableSpace Œ±} (h : m‚ÇÄ ‚â§ m‚ÇÅ) :
    eventuallyMeasurableSpace m‚ÇÄ (ae Œº) ‚â§ eventuallyMeasurableSpace m‚ÇÅ (ae Œº) := by
  rintro s ‚ü®t, ht, hst‚ü©
  exact ‚ü®t, h t ht, hst‚ü©

/-- **Idempotence of the Œº-completion** (the "closure" half). The completion of the completion of
`m‚ÇÄ` is contained in the completion of `m‚ÇÄ`: if `s =·µê t` and `t =·µê u` with `u` `m‚ÇÄ`-measurable, then
`s =·µê u`. -/
theorem eventuallyMeasurableSpace_idem {m‚ÇÄ : MeasurableSpace Œ±} :
    eventuallyMeasurableSpace (eventuallyMeasurableSpace m‚ÇÄ (ae Œº)) (ae Œº) ‚â§
      eventuallyMeasurableSpace m‚ÇÄ (ae Œº) := by
  rintro s ‚ü®t, ‚ü®u, hu, htu‚ü©, hst‚ü©
  exact ‚ü®u, hu, hst.trans htu‚ü©

/-- **Preimage commutes with the Œº-completion** for a quasi-measure-preserving map `f` (in
particular a measure-preserving one). If `s =·µê[Œº] t` then `f‚Åª¬πs =·µê[Œº] f‚Åª¬πt`
(`QuasiMeasurePreserving.preimage_ae_eq`), so an `m‚ÇÄ`-completion set pulled back by `f` is an
`comap f m‚ÇÄ`-completion set:
`comap f (completion m‚ÇÄ) ‚â§ completion (comap f m‚ÇÄ)`. -/
theorem comap_eventuallyMeasurableSpace_le {f : Œ± ‚Üí Œ±} {m‚ÇÄ : MeasurableSpace Œ±}
    (hf : Measure.QuasiMeasurePreserving f Œº Œº) :
    MeasurableSpace.comap f (eventuallyMeasurableSpace m‚ÇÄ (ae Œº)) ‚â§
      eventuallyMeasurableSpace (MeasurableSpace.comap f m‚ÇÄ) (ae Œº) := by
  rintro _ ‚ü®s, ‚ü®t, ht, hst‚ü©, rfl‚ü©
  exact ‚ü®f ‚Åª¬π' t, ‚ü®t, ht, rfl‚ü©, hf.preimage_ae_eq hst‚ü©

/-! ### Mod-0 two-sided generation and coding -/

/-- `P` **two-sidedly generates `(Œ±, e, Œº)` mod 0** when the ambient œÉ-algebra `mŒ±` is contained in
the **Œº-completion** of the two-sided `P`-saturation:
`mŒ± ‚â§ eventuallyMeasurableSpace (twoSidedSat e P) (ae Œº)`.

Equivalently (since `twoSidedSat e P ‚â§ mŒ±` always), the Œº-completions of
`twoSidedSat e P` and of `mŒ±` agree: *every measurable set is recovered, up to a Œº-null set, by the
two-sided `P`-itinerary*. This is the standard "generator mod 0" condition of ergodic theory (see
the file header) and the faithful hypothesis/conclusion of Krieger's theorem ‚Äî the literal equality
`twoSidedSat e P = mŒ±` (`IsGeneratingTwoSided`) is strictly stronger and is not what the classical
construction produces. -/
def IsGeneratingTwoSidedMod0 (e : Œ± ‚âÉ·µê Œ±) (P : MeasurePartition Œº Œπ) : Prop :=
  mŒ± ‚â§ eventuallyMeasurableSpace (twoSidedSat e P) (ae Œº)

/-- **Mod-0 shift-invariance of the two-sided saturation.** For a measure-preserving `e`, pulling
the Œº-completion of `twoSidedSat e P` back by any iterate `e·µê` lands inside it again. Preimage
commutes with the completion (`comap_eventuallyMeasurableSpace_le`, since `e·µê` is
quasi-measure-preserving), and `comap (e·µê) (twoSidedSat e P) ‚â§ twoSidedSat e P` literally
(`comap_twoSidedSat_le`), so completion-monotonicity (`eventuallyMeasurableSpace_mono`) finishes. -/
theorem comap_eventuallyMeasurableSpace_twoSidedSat_le (e : Œ± ‚âÉ·µê Œ±)
    (he : MeasurePreserving (e : Œ± ‚Üí Œ±) Œº Œº) (P : MeasurePartition Œº Œπ) (m : ‚Ñ§) :
    MeasurableSpace.comap (ziter e m)
        (eventuallyMeasurableSpace (twoSidedSat e P) (ae Œº)) ‚â§
      eventuallyMeasurableSpace (twoSidedSat e P) (ae Œº) :=
  le_trans (comap_eventuallyMeasurableSpace_le
      (measurePreserving_ziter e he m).quasiMeasurePreserving)
    (eventuallyMeasurableSpace_mono (comap_twoSidedSat_le e P m))

/-- **Mod-0 recovery / refinement monotonicity.** If every cell of `Q` is recovered mod 0 by the
two-sided `P`-saturation (`œÉ(Q) ‚â§ completion (twoSidedSat e P)`), then the *entire* two-sided
saturation of `Q` is contained in that completion: `twoSidedSat e Q ‚â§ completion (twoSidedSat e P)`.

Each `‚Ñ§`-term `comap (e·µê) œÉ(Q)` of `twoSidedSat e Q` is bounded, by `comap`-monotonicity in the
hypothesis, by `comap (e·µê) (completion (twoSidedSat e P))`, which is bounded by
`completion (twoSidedSat e P)` by mod-0 shift-invariance
(`comap_eventuallyMeasurableSpace_twoSidedSat_le`). Taking the supremum over `m` gives the claim. -/
theorem twoSidedSat_mono_of_codes (e : Œ± ‚âÉ·µê Œ±) (he : MeasurePreserving (e : Œ± ‚Üí Œ±) Œº Œº)
    (P : MeasurePartition Œº Œπ) (Q : MeasurePartition Œº Œ∫)
    (hrec : generatedSigmaAlgebra Œº Q ‚â§ eventuallyMeasurableSpace (twoSidedSat e P) (ae Œº)) :
    twoSidedSat e Q ‚â§ eventuallyMeasurableSpace (twoSidedSat e P) (ae Œº) := by
  rw [twoSidedSat_def (P := Q)]
  refine iSup_le fun m => ?_
  exact le_trans (MeasurableSpace.comap_mono hrec)
    (comap_eventuallyMeasurableSpace_twoSidedSat_le e he P m)

/-- **Recovery lifts a mod-0 two-sided generator.** If `Q` two-sidedly generates `(Œ±, e, Œº)` mod 0
and the two-sided `P`-itinerary recovers each cell of `Q` mod 0
(`œÉ(Q) ‚â§ completion (twoSidedSat e P)`), then `P` two-sidedly generates mod 0 as well.

`mŒ± ‚â§ completion (twoSidedSat e Q)` (by `Q`'s mod-0 generation) and
`completion (twoSidedSat e Q) ‚â§ completion (completion (twoSidedSat e P)) ‚â§ completion
(twoSidedSat e P)` by mod-0 recovery monotonicity (`twoSidedSat_mono_of_codes`),
completion-monotonicity (`eventuallyMeasurableSpace_mono`), and completion-idempotence
(`eventuallyMeasurableSpace_idem`). Chaining gives `mŒ± ‚â§ completion (twoSidedSat e P)`. This is the
mod-0 two-sided analogue of `ErgodicTheory.Entropy.IsGenerating.mono_refine`. -/
theorem IsGeneratingTwoSidedMod0.of_codes {e : Œ± ‚âÉ·µê Œ±}
    (he : MeasurePreserving (e : Œ± ‚Üí Œ±) Œº Œº) {P : MeasurePartition Œº Œπ} {Q : MeasurePartition Œº Œ∫}
    (hQ : IsGeneratingTwoSidedMod0 e Q)
    (hrec : generatedSigmaAlgebra Œº Q ‚â§ eventuallyMeasurableSpace (twoSidedSat e P) (ae Œº)) :
    IsGeneratingTwoSidedMod0 e P :=
  le_trans hQ
    (le_trans (eventuallyMeasurableSpace_mono (twoSidedSat_mono_of_codes e he P Q hrec))
      eventuallyMeasurableSpace_idem)

/-! ### Faithfulness -/

/-- **Faithfulness: the literal condition is stronger than the mod-0 one.** If `P` two-sidedly
generates in the (non-standard) literal sense `twoSidedSat e P = mŒ±` (`IsGeneratingTwoSided`), then
it does so mod 0. Hence the mod-0 statement is a genuine *weakening* of the literal one, and the
headline phrased with `IsGeneratingTwoSidedMod0` is faithful to Krieger's theorem (whose generators
are mod 0) while remaining provable by the classical a.e. construction.

`mŒ± = twoSidedSat e P` (literal generation) embeds into its own Œº-completion by
`le_eventuallyMeasurableSpace`; `le_of_eq ‚Ä¶ .symm` supplies the equality without rewriting under the
`Œº`-indexed completion (which would fail the motive check). The hypothesis `h` is, definitionally,
the equality `twoSidedSat e P = mŒ±` (`IsGeneratingTwoSided` is `@[reducible]`-unfolds to the same
`‚®Ü`-œÉ-algebra as `twoSidedSat`). -/
theorem isGeneratingTwoSidedMod0_of_literal {e : Œ± ‚âÉ·µê Œ±} {P : MeasurePartition Œº Œπ}
    (h : IsGeneratingTwoSided e P) : IsGeneratingTwoSidedMod0 e P :=
  le_trans (le_of_eq h.symm) le_eventuallyMeasurableSpace

end ErgodicTheory.Krieger
